Oracle APEX from the very beginning has been prepared to support large, international projects that can be used in many different countries and need to be adapted to regional standards. During this session I will show how we can prepare fully translated and localized APEX application, that can handle different languages, text directions, time zones, calendars, date/time formats etc. I will also present how should we design our application to support all those features at database and frontend level to be ready to enter new regions and markets within hours.

Just how to make it really global!

During this session, based on my experience in designing, developing and supporting international APEX applications, I would like to show:

- how we can create multilingual APEX applications, using built-in features and open source extensions (plugins, translate-apex.com and OOS);
- which tools and methods used by professional translators can be adapted to APEX development;
- which cultural and regional preferences should we consider when entering new market (e.g. text direction, template design, local habits, formats, different calendars etc.);
- how should we design our database to support internationalization, including NLS settings, time zones support and messages returned from backend and frontend layers;
- how should we plan an application to enter a new market or region without redesign;
- what should we do to get information about user's location and time zones from the browser, to detect default globalization settings or block our service in some countries.

&quot;The classic report is one of the APEX components that are a bit undervalued. It offers great potential when you must adjust the generated HTML after it has been sent to the browser. The session will introduce concepts for creating highly adjustable reports which allow lots of user interaction.

The presentation will introduce a &quot;&quot;no template&quot;&quot; that will open our classic report to use the entire HTML5 box of tricks.

The session will also explain how to hook up external libraries like knockout to your reports.&quot;
